---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';

// Edit me. Each project: problem -> approach -> stack -> result -> links.
const projects = [
	{
		slug: 'differential-serving',
		title: 'Differential serving for CPU→GPU ads ranking',
		year: '2026',
		problem:
			'LinkedIn ads ranking serves a TensorFlow ranker on CPU at internet-scale QPS. A new PyTorch ranker on GPU, served by a separate gRPC inference fleet, promised quality gains but came with a new hardware pool, a new feature pipeline, and a new backend — none of which could become a single point of failure during evaluation. Offline replay missed real-time features, cohort gating, and inventory drift, so a live A/B at request granularity was the only way to learn.',
		approach:
			'Designed and shipped dual-fire serving: a single per-request routing decision in the ads serving orchestrator, gated by experiment treatment, remaining tmax budget (drops the dual-fire whenever the GPU round-trip cannot fit), and a config-driven kill switch. When the gates open, the request is scored by both the CPU champion and the GPU candidate in parallel, with the GPU call issued before the CPU scatter-gather so network I/O fully overlaps. A successful candidate response is adopted; any failure (timeout, RPC error, null) transparently falls back to the champion. Variants run out of process on separate service-discovery partitions so each fleet has its own capacity profile, dependency graph, and ramp/rollback story. On the GPU candidate path: server-side batching across concurrent requests for occupancy, a floor-price prefilter to concentrate scarce GPU capacity on the requests most likely to convert, runtime model-version resolution via the experimentation platform (swap the candidate model without a redeploy), and CPU counterfactual scoring of every GPU-eligible request emitted alongside the served response — so downstream divergence and lift analysis do not need a second serving pass. Authored the RFC and owned the serving-side integration end to end.',
		stack: ['Java', 'PyTorch', 'GPU inference (A100)', 'gRPC inference fleet', 'TensorFlow', 'experimentation platform', 'service discovery'],
		result:
			'Skeleton, feature/scoring path, routing decision, and dual-fire all landed (6 PRs across the scorer and serving services). ~400 QPS sustainable per A100 under a 50ms GPU round-trip budget — sets the tmax gate threshold and the capacity-planning model for the candidate fleet. Three invariant-checked counters (request / adopted / fallback) emitted on every dual-fire decision, dashboarded with an enforced equality invariant. Operator kill switch independent of the experiment lever. Per-request tmax for ads ranking spans roughly 10ms–2s, so the routing decision has to be cheap and tail-safe on the CPU-only fast path; the served path has not regressed in p50/p99 or coverage as the experiment ramps in single-digit increments.',
		links: [],
	},
	{
		slug: 'early-stage-ranking',
		title: 'Early Stage Ranking infra (Two-Tower at ~10M scale)',
		year: '2025–2026',
		problem:
			'The ads delivery funnel ran three loosely-aligned stages — retrieval (~1M → ~3K), a lightweight MLP first-pass ranker (~3K → ~400), and a heavy second-pass ranker (~400 → ~80) — with assorted heuristic filtering and throttling in between. The first two layers were not optimized toward the same objective as the final ranker, leaving real revenue on the table and making the marketplace harder to reason about.',
		approach:
			'Co-designed the infra for an Early Stage Ranking layer that collapses retrieval and first-pass ranking into a single multi-task Two-Tower scoring layer over the entire active creative corpus, followed by centralized-allocation ranking. Member embeddings inferred online per request; creative embeddings generated nearline, fanned out across thousands of shards, and refreshed continuously as creatives or models change. Final scoring is a member-vs-creative dot product on the indexer host. Authored the MS1 design for the embedding pipeline: nearline backfill + periodic refresh, member↔creative version alignment via the embedding-generation service as source of truth, multi-model concurrency for online experimentation, and a backfill-then-activate protocol so a new model version never reaches serving until its embeddings have propagated to every indexer node.',
		stack: ['Java', 'Two-Tower / DLRM', 'Venice', 'Couchbase', 'sharded indexer', 'nearline streaming'],
		result:
			'First end-to-end BST experiment of the new layer landed an over-20% lift in onsite CTR. Architecture validated for ~10M-scale candidate scoring within the existing funnel latency budget; line-of-sight from here to GPU-served ESR.',
		links: [],
	},
	{
		slug: 'entity-cache-rewrite',
		title: 'Entity cache rewrite for the ads serving fleet',
		year: '2021',
		problem:
			'The ads serving service kept all servable entities in memory across hundreds of hosts. Each host bootstrapped and refreshed by going directly to Oracle (via Databus), which created a scalability bottleneck on the database, made cache-miss handling fragile, and was being deprecated. Inside the service, the in-memory cache was deeply coupled with the indexer, which blocked reuse by neighboring services like the pacing/bidding system.',
		approach:
			'Three coordinated RFCs. (1) Built the platform side: an active filter that joins polled Oracle changes with Brooklin change-capture streams, persists to Couchbase, and fans out per-account-partitioned Kafka instructions to clients and a bootstrap server, with a multi-version state machine (NOT_USED → INITIALIZING → BOOTSTRAPPING → RUNNING → CLEANED) so we can iterate schemas, a periodic validator that reconciles cache against Oracle and emits REPLACE corrections, and a low-latency shortcut pipeline for inactivation signals. (2) Decoupled the in-memory cache from the indexer inside the serving service, so the cache layer updates directly from Kafka events and notifies the indexer via a queue. (3) Onboarded the serving service to the new pipeline behind a dark-canary cluster running both pipelines in parallel and diffing them. Lead-authored the decoupling and onboarding RFCs; co-authored the platform RFC.',
		stack: ['Java', 'Kafka', 'Couchbase', 'Brooklin', 'Samza', 'Avro', 'Oracle', 'Rest.li'],
		result:
			'Removed Oracle as a per-host bottleneck for the entire ads-serving fleet. Shipped a portable entity-cache library so neighboring ads services could onboard without rewriting their ingest path. Cutover from Databus validated on a dark-canary cluster running both pipelines and diffing them per-entity.',
		links: [],
	},
];
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={`Projects · ${SITE_TITLE}`} description="Selected engineering projects." />
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<h1>Projects</h1>
			<p>
				A few things I've worked on. Internal LinkedIn work is desensitized where it appears.
			</p>

			{
				projects.map((p) => (
					<article class="project" id={p.slug}>
						<header>
							<h2>
								<a href={`#${p.slug}`}>{p.title}</a>{' '}
								<span class="year">· {p.year}</span>
							</h2>
						</header>
						<dl>
							<dt>Problem</dt>
							<dd>{p.problem}</dd>
							<dt>Approach</dt>
							<dd>{p.approach}</dd>
							<dt>Stack</dt>
							<dd>{p.stack.join(', ')}</dd>
							<dt>Result</dt>
							<dd>{p.result}</dd>
						</dl>
						{p.links.length > 0 && (
							<p>
								{p.links.map((l, i) => (
									<>
										{i > 0 && ' · '}
										<a href={l.href}>{l.label}</a>
									</>
								))}
							</p>
						)}
					</article>
				))
			}
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>

<style>
	.project {
		border-top: 1px solid #ddd;
		padding-top: 1rem;
		margin-bottom: 2rem;
	}
	.project h2 {
		margin: 0 0 0.25em 0;
	}
	.year {
		color: #888;
		font-weight: normal;
		font-size: 0.9em;
	}
	dl {
		margin: 0;
	}
	dt {
		font-weight: 600;
		margin-top: 0.5em;
	}
	dd {
		margin: 0 0 0.5em 0;
	}
</style>
